[src:actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In discrete-time Markov Decision Processes, decisions are made at discrete time intervals.
[src:actor-critic/markov-decision-process] However, for **continuous-time Markov decision processes**, decisions can be made at any time the decision maker chooses.
[src:actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In comparison to discrete-time Markov decision processes, continuous-time Markov decision processes can better model the decision-making process for a system that has continuous dynamics, i.e., the system dynamics are defined by ordinary differential equations (ODEs).
[src:actor-critic/markov-decision-process] This modelling framework can be applied to areas such as queueing systems, epidemic processes, and population processes.
[src:actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Like the discrete-time Markov decision processes, in continuous-time Markov decision processes the agent aims to find the optimal *policy* that would maximize the expected cumulative reward.
[src:actor-critic/markov-decision-process] If the state space and action space are finite, we could use linear programming to find the optimal policy, which was one of the earliest approaches applied.
[src:actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Here we only consider the ergodic model, which means our continuous-time MDP becomes an ergodic continuous-time Markov chain under a stationary policy.
[src:actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Under this assumption, although the decision maker can make a decision at any time in the current state, there is no benefit in taking multiple actions.
[src:actor-critic/markov-decision-process] It is better to take an action only at the time when system is transitioning from the current state to another state.
