[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] In policy-based RL, the actor is a parameterized policy function $\pi _{\theta }$ , where $\theta$ are the parameters of the actor.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The actor takes as argument the state of the environment s and produces a probability distribution $\pi _{\theta }(\cdot \mid s)$ .
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] If the action space is discrete, then $\sum _{a}\pi _{\theta }(a\mid s)=1$ .
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] If the action space is continuous, then $\int _{a}\pi _{\theta }(a\mid s)\mathrm {d} a=1$ .
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The **policy gradient** is defined as $\nabla _{\theta }J(\theta )$ .
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Different policy gradient methods stochastically estimate the policy gradient in different ways.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The goal of any policy gradient method is to iteratively maximize $J(\theta )$ by gradient ascent.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Since the key part of any policy gradient method is the stochastic estimation of the policy gradient, they are also studied under the title of "Monte Carlo gradient estimation".
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The **REINFORCE algorithm**, introduced by Ronald J.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Williams in 1992, was the first policy gradient method.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] By the tower law and the previous lemma.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The score function $\nabla _{\theta }\ln \pi _{\theta }(A_{t}\mid S_{t})$ can be interpreted as the direction in the parameter space that increases the probability of taking action $A_{t}$ in state $S_{t}$ .
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Here, $\alpha _{i}$ is the learning rate at update step i .
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] REINFORCE is an **on-policy** algorithm, meaning that the trajectories used for the update must be sampled from the current policy $\pi _{\theta }$ .
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This can lead to high variance in the updates, as the returns $R(\tau )$ can vary significantly between trajectories.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Many variants of REINFORCE have been introduced, under the title of **variance reduction**.
