[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The natural policy gradient method is a variant of the policy gradient method, proposed by Sham Kakade in 2001.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Unlike standard policy gradient methods, which depend on the choice of parameters $\theta$ (making updates coordinate-dependent), the natural policy gradient aims to provide a coordinate-free update, which is geometrically "natural".
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Inverting $F(\theta )$ is computationally intensive, especially for high-dimensional parameters (e.g., neural networks).
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Practical implementations often use approximations.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The natural gradient descent is theoretically optimal, *if* the objective is truly a quadratic function, but this is only an approximation.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] TRPO's line search and KL constraint attempts to restrict the solution to within a "trust region" in which this approximation does not break down.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This makes TRPO more robust in practice.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Note that in general, other surrogate advantages are possible: $L(\theta ,\theta _{i})=\mathbb {E} _{s,a\sim \pi _{\theta _{i}}}\left[{\frac {\pi _{\theta }(a|s)}{\pi _{\theta _{i}}(a|s)}}\Psi ^{\pi _{\theta _{i}}}(s,a)\right]$ where $\Psi$ is any linear sum of the previously mentioned type.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Indeed, OpenAI recommended using the Generalized Advantage Estimate, instead of the plain advantage $A^{\pi _{\theta }}$ .
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The surrogate advantage $L(\theta ,\theta _{t})$ is designed to align with the policy gradient $\nabla _{\theta }J(\theta )$ .
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Thus it is a "surrogate" of the real objective.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This reduces the problem to a quadratic optimization, yielding the natural policy gradient update: $\theta _{i+1}=\theta _{i}+{\sqrt {\frac {2\epsilon }{g^{T}F^{-1}g}}}F^{-1}g.$ So far, this is essentially the same as natural gradient method.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] A further improvement is proximal policy optimization (PPO), which avoids even computing $F(\theta )$ and $F(\theta )^{-1}$ via a first-order approximation using clipped probability ratios.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] In words, gradient-ascending the new surrogate advantage function means that, at some state $s,a$ , if the advantage is positive: $A^{\pi _{\theta _{t}}}(s,a)>0$ , then the gradient should direct $\theta$ towards the direction that increases the probability of performing action a under the state s .
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] However, as soon as $\theta$ has changed so much that $\pi _{\theta }(a|s)\geq (1+\epsilon )\pi _{\theta _{t}}(a|s)$ , then the gradient should stop pointing it in that direction.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Thus, PPO avoids pushing the parameter update too hard, and avoids changing the policy too much.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] To be more precise, to update $\theta _{t}$ to $\theta _{t+1}$ requires multiple update steps on the same batch of data.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] It would initialize $\theta =\theta _{t}$ , then repeatedly apply gradient descent (such as the Adam optimizer) to update $\theta$ until the surrogate advantage has stabilized.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] It would then assign $\theta _{t+1}$ to $\theta$ , and do it again.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] During this inner-loop, the first update to $\theta$ would not hit the $1-\epsilon ,1+\epsilon$ bounds, but as $\theta$ is updated further and further away from $\theta _{t}$ , it eventually starts hitting the bounds.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] For each such bound hit, the corresponding gradient becomes zero, and thus PPO avoid updating $\theta$ too far away from $\theta _{t}$ .
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This is important, because the surrogate loss assumes that the state-action pair $s,a$ is sampled from what the agent would see if the agent runs the policy $\pi _{\theta _{t}}$ , but policy gradient should be on-policy.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] So, as $\theta$ changes, the surrogate loss becomes more and more *off*-policy.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This is why keeping $\theta$ *proximal* to $\theta _{t}$ is necessary.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This has been used in training reasoning language models with reinforcement learning from human feedback.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) is a minor variant of PPO that omits the value function estimator V .
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] That is, it is the standard score of the rewards.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] As before, the KL penalty term can be applied to encourage the trained policy to stay close to a reference policy.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] GRPO was first proposed in the context of training reasoning language models by researchers at DeepSeek.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Methods like TRPO, PPO and natural policy gradient share a common idea - while the policy should be updated in the direction of the policy gradient, the update should be done in a safe and stable manner, typically measured by some distance with respect to the policy before the update.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] A similar notion of update stability is found in proximal convex optimization techniques like Mirror Descent.
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This leads to reconsidering the policy update procedure as an optimization procedure aimed at finding an optimal policy, in the (non-convex) optimization landscape of the underlying Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] In fact, the KL divergence penalty also appears in the original PPO paper, suggesting the MDPO perspective as a theoretical unification of the main derivation concepts behind many concurrent policy gradient techniques.
